Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.Instrument.NISP.NISPBadPixelsFile
Parameter.Description: The bad pixels are identified on one representative detector. They are then simulated for the entire focal plane (16 detectors). The file contains 16 extensions (one extension per detector): H2RG_1_1 H2RG_1_2 H2RG_1_3 H2RG_1_4 H2RG_2_1 H2RG_2_2 H2RG_2_3 H2RG_2_4 H2RG_3_1 H2RG_3_2 H2RG_3_3 H2RG_3_4 H2RG_4_1 H2RG_4_2 H2RG_4_3 H2RG_4_4 Each extension is a 1D data cube with dimensions 2040x2040 the map of bad pixels: 0 = BAD PIXEL 1 = GOOD PIXEL. For each pixel the following quantities were computed: CDS noise, Photometry Y dark and noise, Photometry J dark and noise,Photometry H dark and noise, Spectrometric dark and noise, Additionally the disconnected pixels (identifed as pixels whose response is zero in presence of an external source) were identifed. For each of the quantities enumerated above a threshold value was defined and an image of flagged pixels (whose value is higher or equal to the threshold) was constructed per quantity. The final map of bad pixels was then constructed as the logic sum of the partial flag images. The threshold values chosen for bad pixels definitions are reported in the Table 1 of the TN mentioned in the source section.
Parameter.Source: Input by Anne Ealet/Bogna Kubik See technical note : EUCL-IPN-TN-7-020 Ed1 Rev2

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.Instrument.NISP.NISPEffectiveIntegrationTime
Parameter.Description: The effective integration time tint is given for each readout mode of the NISP. This tint is expressed as: tint = tframe * (N-1) * (D + M) for a given MACC(N,M,D) readout mode and for a given tframe frame time. This time is used for the Signal to Noise Ratio computation. For operational efficiency computation refers to Total Integration Time parameter. The order (column of the table) of the read out mode is : NISP Spectroscopic mode for Red Grism, NISP Photometric mode for band Y, NISP Photometric mode for band J, NISP Photometric mode for band H.

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.Instrument.NISP.NISPYPSF
Parameter.Description: NISP-P PSFs are provided in 16 FITS files for each filter corresponding to the centre of the 16 detectors on the NISP focal plane array, resulting in 48 files (3 filters x 16 positions). The files can be identified by the detector identity number at the end of the FITS file name after the last underscore character, and the filter identifier Y, J and H after EUC_NISP-P. These are : - optical monochromatic PSFs at 3 wavelengths over the passband for the filter - without detector inter-pixel response variation - without AOCS - with the pixel size of 3um (1/6 of NISP pixel size) The extension number for a given set of parameters can be found using the vector data in the Primary extension (extension 0), which gives the wavelengths of all the following extensions.
Parameter.Source: Patrick Hudelot/Koryo Okumura for SC456.

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.Instrument.NISP.NISPSPSF
Parameter.Description: NISP-S PSFs are provided in 16 FITS files corresponding to the centre of the 16 detectors on the NISP focal plane array. The files can be identified by the detector identity number at the end of the FITS file name after the last underscore character. Each FITS file contains monochromatic PSFs at 10 wavelengths for each grism (4 in total), in each order (3 in total), suming up to 120 PSFs in total. These are : - optical monochromatic PSFs at 10 wavelengths over the passband for the red grisms and 9 wavelengths for the blue grism (the largest wavelength PSF is included twice to make them 10 for a historical reason) - without detector inter-pixel response variation - without AOCS - with the pixel size of 3um (1/6 of NISP pixel size) The extension number for a given set of parameters can be found using the data cube in the Primary extension (extension 0). For example, n-th wavelength of m-th grism in l-th order can be found in the extension given by f[0].data[m, l, n] in python.
Parameter.Source: Patrick Hudelot/Koryo Okumura for SC456.

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.Instrument.NISP.NISPSPSF_order_1
Parameter.Description: This is the constant NISP Spectro PSF for the 3 orientations given at order 1 : R1/R2/R3 to be used for Scientific challenge3. This PSF is provided into two fits files corresponding to different pixelscale sizes. The file xx_OSAMP.fits files has 3um pixelscale (1/6th of Euclid NISP pixelscale). The other file has the native NISP pixelscale. These PSF's are provided at a unique wavelength that is : 1505nm - These PSF's are taken from the center of the FPA and will be used for the whole field (constant in the field). - These PSF's have AOCS included. - They have been generated using a "solar type" spectrum (closest Teff,logg,FeH parameters) from the BaSeL SED library.

Parameter.Description: DESCRIPTION OF THE FORMAT OF THE EUC_NISP_H2RG-NONLINEARITY-CORRECTION-COEFFICIENTS_2027*.FITS Nonlinearity correction coefficients are measured for spectrometric and photo H readout mode on one representative detector. They are then simulated for the entire focal plane (16 detectors). (c.f. Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.Instrument.NISP.NISPQEFile
Parameter.Description: For each SCA, the quantum efficiency was measured by DCL at 40 wavelengths between 600 nm and 2550nm. There is one file per detector, the naming pattern is qe_SCA_18XXX_mdb_v1.fits, with 18XXX the SCA id. In each fits file, the primary hdu contains no data but the header gives you the number of wavelength (NUMWAVES=40), the wavelength range (WAVRANGE='600-2550') and the unit of QE values (UNITS='%QE') (and other information about the condition of the QE measurement). Each following extension contains a map of QE (in percentage) for a given wavelength. The wavelength is saved in the header keyword WAVELEN. the extension name pattern is WAVELENXXXnm with XXX the wavelength. QE value can exceed 100% or be negative due to experimental errors.
Parameter.Source: Input by Remi Barbier (Detector scientist)

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.Instrument.NISP.NISPBadPixelMask
Parameter.Description: All three sets are from the Goddard Detector Testing Lab on the Euclid detectors which were used to pick arrays for delivery to the Euclid Consortia. The file names have the detector ID from NISPDetectorSlots.table which is already in the MDB. The descriptions that follow use the model description for the QE files. The files that start with cds_noise: For each SCA the CDS noise was measured for all pixels at DCL. There is one file per detector, the naming pattern is cds_noise_SCA_18XXX_mdb_v1.fits, with 18XXX the SCA id. The pixel value is the CDS noise in unites of electrons. The files that start with dpix: For each SCA disconnected pixels which yield unusable measurements were identified at DCL. There is one file per detector, the naming pattern is dpix_SCA_18XXX_mdb_v1.fits, with 18XXX the SCA id. The pixel value is 1 for good pixels and 0 for disconnected pixels. The files that start with full_well: For each SCA the full well of pixels were measured at DCL. There is one file per detector, the naming pattern is full_well_SCA_18XXX_mdb_v1.fits, with 18XXX the SCA id. Only the data pixels (2040x2040) are reported for this measurement with reference pixels removed. The pixel value is the full well of the detector in electrons. Pixels with values less than 0 have no usable full well.
Parameter.Source: Input by Peter Capak/A. Bonchi

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.Instrument.NISP.NISPTotalIntegrationTime
Parameter.Description: The total integration time ttot is given for each readout mode of the NISP. This is the time between the first pixel of the first frame of the first group and the last pixel of the last frame of the last group and can be expressed as: ttot = tframe * (D * (N-1) + N * M) for a given MACC(N,M,D) readout mode. This time is used for the operational efficiency of the survey. For SNR computation refers to Effective Integration Time parameter. The order (column of the table) of the read out mode is : NISP Spectroscopic mode for Red Grism, NISP Photometric mode for band Y, NISP Photometric mode for band J, NISP Photometric mode for band H.

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.Instrument.NISP.NISPDistortionMaps
Parameter.Description: These are the NISP Distortion Maps per NISP photometric channel to be used for SC3. Parameter.Source: Input by Patrick Hudelot.

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.Instrument.NISP.NISPSDistortionMaps
Parameter.Description: These are the NISP - S distortion maps for the spectroscopic channel, to be used for SC4/5/6. Those data was computed with zemax and provided by Patrick Hudelot. Currently, the data are available for one grism, for the first order, at 10 wavelengths on a 256 x 256 pixel grid. For each grism, those data are contained in a fits file, one extension per wavelength and per dispersion order. Each extension, ie each combination [wavelength, order, grism] is a data cube of: * the relative input coordinates in the telescope, 'FIELD X' and 'FIELD Y ' in degree and * output coordinates on the detector, 'X' and 'Y' in mm. In the data provided by Patrick, there is also additional data, not use for now: * the Z coordinate and * the projected input coordinates l,m and n. We added two keyword in the extension header: * 'LAMBDA' the wavelength in Angstrom and * 'ORDER' the dispersion order number. The extension name follow the schema 'O#_#p##', with 'O#' referring to the dispersion order and '#p##' to the wavelength (in um as in the file name provided by Patrick). The first extension of each file contains additional header keywords relative to the zemax data: * 'O#_NLAMBDA' the number of wavelength for each order * 'O#_MAP_#' the extension name containing the data for each order and each wavelength * 'ASTRODIST' the data used to compute the astrometric distortion (at the blaze wavelength). We also fit the dispersion/distortion model of the axesim software (see http://axe.stsci.edu/axe/manual/html/), the parameters of this model are also in the first extension header, for each grism order: * 'O#_DLDP_ORDER', the order of the polynomial function DLDP, * 'O#_DLDP_XYO' the order of the DLDP polynomial parameters (for the field dependency) * 'O#_DLDP_##' the parameter value * 'O#_DYDX_ORDER', the order of the polynomial function DYDX * 'O#_DYDX_XYO' the order of the DYDX polynomial parameters (for the field dependency) * 'O#_DYDX_##' the parameter value. References: * zemax data: note coming soon (Patrick) * transfert function: note coming soon (Julien)
Parameter.Source: Input by Patrick Hudelot and Nicolas Fourmanoit

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.Instrument.NISP.NISPDistortionOffsetFWATilt
Parameter.Description: These maps describe the distortion offset in the focal plane for a NISP filter wheel assembly (FWA) tilt for the NISP Y-band filter. The maps return the offset in micrometers for x- and y-positions for either a 1mm tilt at the filter position, or equally a 0.357142857degree tilt angle of the FWA. The pixel coordinates in the maps are defined in the same way as in the regular distortion maps SpaceSegment.Instrument.NISP.NISPDistortionMaps: FITS WCS parameters map pixel coordinates to positions (tan(x_angle-x_centre),tan(y_angle-y_centre)), where (x_centre,y_centre) is the light ray angle for the focal plane centre. Given offsets(x_tilt_distortion_offset,y_tilt_distortion_offset)and using regular distortion maps to define focal plane positions (x_distorted,y_distorted), the overall distortion is computed, e.g. for x-coordinates, as x_distorted + (tilt_in_degrees/0.357142857) * x_tilt_distortion_offset.
Parameter.Source: Input by Gregor Seidel.

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.Instrument.NISP.NISPFlatField
Parameter.Description: Flat is computed for the following readout mode: ========================================================================= ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ MODE MACC(NG, NF, ND) T_EXP T_INT [sec] [sec] ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ photo H MACC(3,16,5) 82 59 ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ F_E = 1.3 - average conversion gain [electrons/ADU] T_F = 1.41 - single frame read time [sec] T_EXP = [ NG*NF + (NG - 1)*ND ]*T_F - total exposure time [sec] T_INT = (NG - 1) * (NF + ND )*T_F - effective integration time [sec] ========================================================================= 7 exposures with increasing fluxes are used to generated the raw data 20, 40, 60, 80, 100, 120, 140 e-/sec Each exposure is fitted by the LSF (gives and image of slopes a_{ij} in [ADU/fr]) and the flat field is computed as f_{ij} = a_{ij}/average(a) where average(a) is the spatial average of the slopes image. The output file is generated for each exposure: ========================================================================= EUC_NISP-H2RG-flat-*-SC3_**.fits The '*' in the file name indicates the nominal flux in e-/sec. Example: EUC_NISP-H2RG-flat-140-SC3_**.fits was generated for the flat field with the incident nominal flux of 140 e/sec. Each output file contains: ========================================================================= map per detector - flat field correction coefficients f_{ij}
Parameter.Source: Input by Anne Ealet/Bogna Kubik.

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.Instrument.NISP.NISPSaturation
Parameter.Description: SC3 simulations will have a constant saturation value of 65535 for all pixels (16-bit integer limit). However, threshold wont be constant for a realistic case, and therefore the saturation module is expecting to read a frame containing saturation data. So, this mock input fits file containing 16 extensions, with a 2040x2040 image each, filled with 65535 to get ready for the realistic case being at the same time compliant with SC3 simulations has been generated.
Parameter.Source: Input by Peter Capak. For SC3 only.

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.Instrument.NISP.NISPCalibrationUnitIlluminationMap
Parameter.Description: This mock illumination map describes the non-homogeneous illumination pattern of the NISP near infrared calibration unit (NI-CU) in its first FITS extension, with the aim of potentially extending the file in future to account for varying patterns for each LED and over the survey time. In that case, image extension keys LED and VAR will designate a specific LED and pattern variation for that LED, while primary header keys LEDS and VARS will set the number of LEDs and variations per LED stored in the FITS file. At the moment, these keys can be ignored. The map is normalised to a mean value of 1 per pixel, and the FITS WCS parameters map pixel coordinates to a focal plane position in micrometers, centred on the centre of the detector array. Values between pixels should be interpolated using splines, although in the current representation linear interpolation produces negligible errors.
Parameter.Source: Input by Gregor Seidel, 2018-09-25

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.Instrument.NISP.NISPCULEDA
Parameter.Description: Averaged wavelength-dependent emission characteristics of the NI-CU calibration source at 135K. There are 5 LEDs (labelled A, B, C, D, and E) each emitting around one specific wavelength. This emitted spectral energy distribution should not change with absolute fluence level, hence this is a relative emission scaled to lie between 0 and 1. However, there will be changes with temperature. Data for other temperatures (110K, 145K, 298K) exist but are not part of the MDB right now. There is no data shortward of ~900nm, which affects the completeness of the LED type "A". Origin of these data are (noisy) measurements from the qualification campaigns by "von Hoerner and Sulger" (Schwetzingen, Germany), the manufacturer of NI-CU.
Parameter.Source: Input by Knud Jahnke, 2018-02-21

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.Instrument.NISP.NISPBaselineFile
Parameter.Description: The baseline is the mean value in ADU of the first group value. For each SCA, the baseline file contains the baseline value of each pixel. The file is a fits files with an empty primary HDU containing in its header information about the data acquisition. The second HDU, named 'b_g' contains the baseline value of each pixel. The file naming pattern is baseline_{SCS number}_mdb_v{version number}.fits. At the moment, only the baseline of the SCS 18249 is available.
Parameter.Source: Input by Remi Barbier (Detector scientist)

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.Instrument.NISP.NISPKTCFile
Parameter.Description: The KTC is the standard deviation of the baseline (the first group value) in ADU. For each SCA, the KTC file contains the KTC value of each pixel. The file is a fits files with an empty primary HDU containing in its header information about the data acquisition. The second HDU, named 'ktc_g' contains the KTC value of each pixel. The file naming pattern is ktc_{SCS number}_mdb_v{version number}.fits. At the moment, only the ktc of the SCS 18249 is available.
Parameter.Source: Input by Remi Barbier (Detector scientist)

Parameter.title: Environment.Galaxy.Outstray.NISPGROutfieldTelescopestraylightmaplambda1600nmCBEmaxGalCor
Parameter.Description: This is the telescope contribution to outfield straylight based on the reference NDI model for the NISP Red Grism mode. The map gives for pointing in galactic coordinates the contribution of outfield straylight in the NISP focal plane expressed in e-/s/pix. The outfield straylight is considered constant over the instrument field of view, as an integral of all the outfield flux coming from the full sky stars. The CBE minimum case is computed based on the maximum CBE telescope and NISP photon conversion efficiency.
Parameter.Source: Input by J.A Mission straylight performance analysis EUCL-SAP-RP-5-001 issue 1.0. Current Best Estimate maximum.

Parameter.title: Environment.Galaxy.ExtinctionEBmVMapGalCoord
Parameter.Description: This is the galactic dust extinction map to be used for SC456. The common Galactic Extinction map is the Planck 2013 map : HFI_CompMap_ThermalDustModel_2048_R1_20 available here : http://pla.esac.esa.int/pla/aio/product-action?MAP.MAP_ID=HFI_CompMap_ThermalDustModel_2048_R1.20.fits. Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.PLM.PLMVISPSF95pcWFE800nm
Parameter.Description: This is the PSF of the VIS channel telescope for 9 fields in the VIS focal Plane. The PSF is monochromatic at 800 nm. The realization of the tolerancing associated to this set is such that the worst PSF over the field as a WFE close to the WFE limits for 95% of the tolerancing cases. This is considered as a typical design case for analysis at PDR. Additional details information in the header of the fits file (image plane PSF sampling if 0.004 mm, image size 256x256 PSF sampling steps). The PSF are generated by Airbus as part of the PDR delivery.
Parameter.Source: Input by J.A. As Designed. RUN PDR _140310.

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.PLM.TelescopeVISPlatescale
Parameter.Description: For real system. the focal length is not unique. It depends on the field point P of the FOV and on the orientation teta z WRT the frame of the FPA. Local Focal Length is defined as the ratio between ds and du: LFL=ds/du : du defines the elementary angle between the directions of two beams in the object space of the Telescope. ds defines the elementary distance between the two focused points at the focal plane level relative to the two beams. The Local Focal Length centre is the central value of the focal length distribution. Unit is arcsec/micron
Parameter.Source: Input by J.L.A. As required. Euclid SRD (EUCL-EST-RD-1-002 v1.2) Requirement SRD-PLM-38.

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.PLM.TelescopeVISPSFEllipticity
Parameter.Description: This is the VIS Channel PSF maximum ellipticity at 800 nm including spacecraft effect. The ellipticity is defined in terms of the Gaussian weighted quadrupole moments: dsqrt ( e1*e1 + e2*e2) Where e1 and e2 are the two projected ellipticity components obtained from the quadrupole moments. The Gaussian weighting function has a standard deviation =0.75 arcsec. based on the typical size of the smallest galaxies useful for weak lensing. The ellipticity is defined at the FPA level using the second order moment expressed at FPA level.
Parameter.Source: Input by J.L.A. Euclid SRD (EUCL-EST-RD-1-002 v1.2) Requirement SRD-PLM-25. As Required

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.PLM.TelescopeVISPSFEllipticityStability
Parameter.Description: This is the VIS channel PSF variation of the quadratic radius (DeltaR2/R2) at 800nm (including contributions from pointing error) at any point of the VIS channel FoV between any of the 8 consecutive dither exposures of two adjacent survey fields.
Parameter.Source: Input by J.L.A. Euclid SRD (EUCL-EST-RD-1-002 v1.2) Requirement SRD-PLM-28. As Required

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.PLM.TelescopeVISPSFFWHM
Parameter.Description: This is the VIS channel PSF maximum FWHM at 800 nm for any point of the field of view including spacecraft effects. The requirement value includes contributions from design residuals. integration alignment error. focus error. and PLM thermal stability. It does not include the VIS instrument contribution. nor the spacecraft induced image motion (e.g. AOCS and SVM thermo-elastic effects).
Parameter.Source: This is the system FWHM. Input by J.L.A. Euclid SRD (EUCL-EST-RD-1-002 v1.2) Requirement SRD-PLM-24. As Required

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.PLM.TelescopeVISPSFLambdaParameterAlpha
Parameter.Description: This is the VIS telescope PSF wavelength dependence. The wavelength dependence is described with a power index (alpha) with FWHM(lambda) proportional to lambda x alpha.
Parameter.Source: Input by J.L.A. Euclid SRD (EUCL-EST-RD-1-002 v1.2) Requirement SRD-PLM-27. As Required

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.PLM.TelescopeVISPSFR2
Parameter.Description: This is the VIS channel PSF profile maximum size at 800nm defined by the R^2 parameter including spacecraft effects. R^2 is the size defined by the quadrupole moments: R^2=Qxx+Qyy.
Parameter.Source: This is the system R2. Input by J.LA. Euclid SRD (EUCL-EST-RD-1-002 v1.2) Requirement SRD-PLM-26. As Required

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.PLM.TelescopeVISPSFR2Stability
Parameter.Description: This is the VIS channel PSF variation of the quadratic radius (deltaR2/R2) at 800nm (including contributions from pointing error) at any point of the VIS channel FoV between any of the 8 consecutive dither exposures of two adjacent survey fields.
Parameter.Source: Input by J.L.A. Euclid SRD (EUCL-EST-RD-1-002 v1.2) Requirement SRD-PLM-29. As Required

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.PLM.PLMVISPSFLambdaFPA
Parameter.Description: This Optical VIS PSF is a set of 36 files (308GB). VIS PSF to be used with ELViS/SHE_PSF are provided in 36 FITS files corresponding to the 36 CCDs of the VIS focal plane. The files can be identified by the CCD identity number nm at the end of the string : EUC_SIM_VIS-PSF-nm. These PSFs are computed over a grid of spatial positions and for 8 wavelengths over the VIS passband. The PSF images have a resolution of 4um (1/3 of a EC pixel). The first data extension contains the PSF images in a 4D table (position, wavelength, 2D PSF image), the second table extension contains a catalog listing the Field of View position of the PSFs. Warning : Take care that the new optical PSF should NOT be convolved by the AOCS and detector PSF. This is now done inside ELViS. The PSFs have been computed using the SHE_PSM code (Duncan et al). The input data for this code are Zemax simulations from the optical model pdr_cool_69_v.1.seq. This model represents a cold telescope without polishing errors and without coating wavefront errors. The FOV distorsion was extracted from the Chiefray file EUCLID_PHASE_B2_VIS_Chief_ray_coordinates.fits.
Parameter.Source: Input by Patrick Hudelot for SC456.

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.SVM.DitherStepAngularError
Parameter.Description: This is the maximum error applicable to each dither step (per axis). The dither step shall therefore always be between DitherStepAngularMinimum and DitherStepAngularMinimum + DitherStepAngularError.
Parameter.Source: Input by J.A. As Required. MOCD part A (issue2.0)

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.SVM.DitherStepAngularMinimum
Parameter.Description: This is the Minimum dither steps to be applied between each dither of a Nominal Science Observation Sequence. The Ysc shift corresponds to a shift of line of sight along direction Ysc (rotation around Xsc axis). and the Xsc shift correspond to a shift of line of sight along direction Xsc (rotation around the Ysc axis). Value to be confirmed
Parameter.Source: Input by J.A. As Required. MOCD part A (issue2.0)

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.SVM.MaxField2FieldOverlap
Parameter.Description: The survey is performed tiling the sky through geometrically contiguous tiles. where the size of each tile corresponds to the maximum common area between the VIS and NISP fields of view. The maximum linear overlap between tiles is MaxField2FieldOverlap % overlap between adjacent fields (3 sigma case).
Parameter.Source: Input by J.A. As Required. MOCD part A (issue2.0)

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.SVM.MaxLargeSlewAngleXsc
Parameter.Description: A large slew is defined as a slew with amplitude larger than Nominal.Slew.Amplitude. One large slew shall have a maximum amplitude of MaxLargeSlewAngleXsc rotation about the XSC axis.
Parameter.Source: Input by J.A. As Required. MOCD part A (issue2.0)

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.SVM.MaxLargeSlewAngleYsc
Parameter.Description: A large slew is defined as a slew with amplitude larger than 1.2 deg. One large slew shall have a maximum amplitude of Max.Large.Slew.Angle.Ysc rotation about the YSC axis.
Parameter.Source: Input by J.A. As Required. MOCD part A (issue2.0)

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.SVM.MaxLargeSlewAngleZsc
Parameter.Description: A large slew is defined as a slew with amplitude larger than 1.2 deg. One large slew shall have a maximum amplitude of Max.Large.Slew.Angle.Zsc rotation about the ZSC axis.
Parameter.Source: Input by J.A. As Required. MOCD part A (issue2.0)

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.SVM.MinField2FieldOverlap
Parameter.Description: The survey is performed tiling the sky through geometrically contiguous tiles. where the size of each tile corresponds to the maximum common area between the VIS and NISP fields of view. The minimum linear overlap between tiles is Min.Field2Field.overlap % overlap between adjacent fields (3 sigma case). This minimum overlap ensure no gaps between fields (disconnected fields are not allowed).
Parameter.Source: Input by J.A. As Required. MOCD part A (issue2.0)

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.SVM.NominalDitherSlewDuration
Parameter.Description: The dither step is the different in pointing between two consecutive dithers of the same Science Observation. A dither is a sequence of operations performed with the telescope pointed to a fixed portion of the sky consisting of one exposure in the visible channel. one in the near-infrared in spectroscopic mode. and one exposure for the three bands Y. J and H.
Parameter.Source: Input by J.A. As Required. MOCD part A (issue2.0)

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.SVM.NominalFieldSlewDuration
Parameter.Description: A nominal Field slew duration is duration of slew between 2 consecutive pointing defining a Nominal Science Operations. Its maximum size is defined by the NominalSlewAmplitude parameter.
Parameter.Source: Input by J.A. As Required. MOCD part A (issue2.0)

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.SVM.NominalLargeSlewVelocity
Parameter.Description: A large slew is defined as a slew with amplitude larger than NominalSlewAmplitude. Large slews are performed at slew rate of NominalLargeSlewVelocity. Unit is deg/minute
Parameter.Source: Input by J.A. As Required. MOCD part A (issue2.0)

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.SVM.NominalScienceObservationSequenceDuration
Parameter.Description: One Science Observation is the complete sequence of VIS and NISP data taking and instruments operations on one Survey Field. including 4 dithers
Parameter.Source: Input by J.A. As Required.MOCD part A (issue2.0)

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.SVM.NominalSlewAmplitude
Parameter.Description: A slew is a manoeuvre of the Spacecraft from one attitude to another without specific constraint on the path. The nominal slew is the slew between two consecutive Nominal Science Observations. Any slew larger than nominal slew amplitude is considered from S/C as a large slew.
Parameter.Source: Input by J.A. As Required. MOCD part A (issue2.0)

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.SVM.NumberOfOperationMax
Parameter.Description: This is the total number of Nominal Science Operations and Calibrations. One Science Observation is the complete sequence of VIS and NISP data taking and instruments operations on one Survey Field. including 4 dithers. In this allocation. each calibration operations is assumed to be equivalent to a Nominal Science Operation in terms of propellant consumptions (this is an approximation acceptable for allocation).
Parameter.Source: Input by J.A. As Required. MOCD part A (issue2.0)

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.SVM.RollAlphaAngleMax
Parameter.Description: The Alpha angle is defined as the angle between the Sun vector projected onto the XSC YSC plane and the +XSC axis. It increases as the spacecraft rotates clockwise about its +ZSC axis.
Parameter.Source: Input by J.A. As Required. MOCD part A (issue2.0)

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.SVM.RollAlphaAngleMin
Parameter.Description: The Alpha angle is defined as the angle between the Sun vector projected onto the XSCYSC plane and the +XSC axis. It increases as the spacecraft rotates clockwise about its +ZSC axis.
Parameter.Source: Input by J.A. As Required. MOCD part A (issue2.0)

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.SVM.SolarAspectAngleMax
Parameter.Description: The Solar Aspect Angle (SAA) is defined as the angle between the spacecraft +Zsc axis (telescope pointing direction) and the direction to the centre of the solar disk.
Parameter.Source: Input by J.A. As Required. MOCD part A (issue2.0)

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.SVM.SolarAspectAngleMin
Parameter.Description: The Solar Aspect Angle (SAA) is defined as the angle between the spacecraft +Zsc axis (telescope pointing direction) and the direction to the centre of the solar disk.
Parameter.Source: Input by J.A. As Required. MOCD part A (issue2.0)

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.Instrument.VIS.CUUniformityMapNormalised
Parameter.Description: VIS CU non-uniformity map given from CU normalized to unity at maximum over the VIS Focal Plane. This is a polynomial fit (order 3 in 2D) of the previous map provided by IAS The map is slightly oversized with respect to the VIS Focal Plane such that for the nominal size of the focal plane, the active pixels are located within [X0=11, X1=180] and [Y0=20, Y1=172], indexed from 1. Current map does not include all effects, for example the integrating sphere non-uniformity at the exit port.
Parameter.Source: Input by S.N. As required. EUCL-EST-RS-6-001 v3.0

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.Instrument.VIS.VISCCDChargeInjection
Parameter.Description: This is the size of the charge injection structure that splits the CCD in the vertical direction.
Parameter.Source: Input from J. Denniston EUCL-MSS-ICD-6-002 issue1.1. As Required

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.Instrument.VIS.VISCCDColumn
Parameter.Description: This is the number of CCD on a column of the VIS focal plane assembly.
Parameter.Source: Input by J.A. As required. Not validated. For test in the MDB.

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.Instrument.VIS.VISCCDDefectsColumnEOL
Parameter.Description: This is the number of CCD column defects after irradiation to qualification levels. Column defects are any column that contains at least 100 white or dark pixel defects.
Parameter.Source: Input by J.A. . Not validated, for test in the MDB. EUCL-EST-RS-6-001 v3.0. As Required

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.Instrument.VIS.VISCCDDefectsTotalSpotsEOL
Parameter.Description: This is the total number of CCD spots defects after irradiation to qualification levels. Spots are white and black spots. White spots are pixels that have a generation rate greater than or equal to 300 e-/pixel/minute at 173 K (This is equivalent to 100 e-/pixel/hour at 153K). *Black spots are pixels that have a signal less than 80% of the local mean signal under uniform illumination at a global mean signal level of 50% image FWC.
Parameter.Source: Input by J.A. As required. Not validated, for test in the MDB. EUCL-EST-RS-6-001 v3.0

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.Instrument.VIS.VISCCDDefectsTrapsEOL
Parameter.Description: This is the number of CCD traps defects after irradiation to qualification levels. Traps are any pixel where charge is temporarily held and the trapping capacity is greater than 200 e-.
Parameter.Source: Input by J.A. As required. Not validated, for test in the MDB. EUCL-EST-RS-6-001 v3.0

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.Instrument.VIS.VISCCDDefectsWhiteSpotsBOL
Parameter.Description: This is the number of CCD white spots defects beginning of life. White spots are pixels that have a generation rate greater than or equal to 300 e-/pixel/minute at 173 K (This is equivalent to 100 e-/pixel/hour at 153K).
Parameter.Source: Input by J.A. As required. Not validated, for test in the MDB. EUCL-EST-RS-6-001 v3.0

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.Instrument.VIS.VISCCDDefectsWhiteSpotsEOL
Parameter.Description: This is the number of CCD white spots defects after irradiation to qualification levels. White spots are pixels that have a generation rate greater than or equal to 300 e-/pixel/minute at 173 K (This is equivalent to 100 e-/pixel/hour at 153K).
Parameter.Source: Input by J.A. As required. Not validated, for test in the MDB. EUCL-EST-RS-6-001 v3.0

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.Instrument.VIS.VISCCDGapLongDimensionNominalImage

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.Instrument.VIS.GhostModel
Parameter.Description: The ghost model will be given from a Zemax study made before the flight, and will be refined with data accumulated during the PV phase. From the reference model (EUCLID_Phase_B2_VIS.zmx and EUCLID_Phase_B2_NISP.zmx), a non-sequential model including VIS and NISP has been built and is proposed for the Scientific challenge 2. The dichroic is modelled as a window with a 50/50 beam splitter on the front surface and a tilted mirror on a back surface. Each ghost is a defocused and fainter image of the previous ghost image. Only the first order (first image of the ghost) is processed. A polynomial fit (order 3) allows to compute the shift (deltaX, deltaY) between the ghost and the primary image with matrices A and B. Y = ( 1 y y^2 y^3) X = ( 1 x x^2 x^3) DeltaX = Y A X DeltaY = Y B X Inputs x and y are angles in degrees (field position in Euclid). Outputs deltaX deltaY are in millimeters in the detector plane. The study about the dependance of the position of the ghost with wavelength and position in the field is described in the technical note.
Parameter.Source: Input by Patrick Hudelot/Samuel Ronayette from Ghost Model for the V0 VIS prototype and VIS simulator used for the Scientific challenge 2, these files have been processed by Samuel Ronayette with ZEMAX from an optical model. Note prepared by S. Ronayette, DSM / IRFU / SAp, CEA Saclay date: 16/07/2013 MAJ: 10/10/2013.Not validated. To be used for SC2 and make SIM and PF in sync. Current best Estimate

This model has been produced on a dense star field with a non-nominal variable PSF model (SIM was not able to produce nominal PSF outside the scope of an official request from VIS).

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.Instrument.VIS.VISOpticsAOCSPixelDetectorPSF

The wavefront are combined using the spectral energy distribution of the Sun (Teff = 5750, logg = 4.5 et Fe/H=0.0 in the BaSeL 2.2 library) and the current best model of the VIS band transmission and detector QE from the MDB. Additional effects, such as the AOCS, pixel response and detector PSF, are also included.
Parameter.Source: Input by Patrick Hudelot / Alexandre Boucaud

Parameter.title: SpaceSegment.Instrument.VIS.PRNU
Parameter.Description: Taking the characterization results from the manufacturer (e2v-teledyne) before delivery of the flight CCDs, the average values PRNU are 1.2, 1.0 and 0.9% at 550, 750 and 900 nm, respectively. The worst device has a PRNU of 1.6-1.8% at 550 nm. Not all the delivered flight devices will actually fly, some may be used for ground testing or kept as spares, so the final averages will vary. Lets take a 20% pessimistic margin, to have representative values of PRNU for most flight CCDs.

Parameter.title: Survey.Calibration.Sources.NGC_6803_PN
Parameter.Description: This compact elliptical PN has a uniformly bright disk with no apparent structure in the optical and is surrounded by a fainter halo about twice the size of the bright shell (Schwarz et al. 1992). In the KSPEC imaging channel, however, the PN was seen to be double lobed, with the lobes on the minor axis of the bright elliptical region. Spectra were obtained at two positions, one centered on the E lobe, and the other position 5'' NW in the halo region. The lobe spectrum shows bright H I and He I lines, with a stellar continuum contribution out to about 1.5 km. There is also unidentified line emission at 2.286 um. The halo spectrum is quite different, with weak Pab and continuum emission, and is probably reflected star and nebular emission. The data is in a fits file. The primary HDU is empty and contains in its header the following information (from CDS): RAD_VEL:13.1:Radial Velocity, 1953GCRV..C......0W ERR_RV:2:Radial Velocity, 1953GCRV..C......0W REDSHIFT:0.000044:1953GCRV..C......0W ERR_Z:0.000007:1953GCRV..C......0W MAG_B:12.700:2003yCat.2246....0C MAG_V:15.2 MAG_R:10.600:2003yCat.2246....0C MAG_J:11.912:2003yCat.2246....0C ERR_J:0.033:2003yCat.2246....0C MAG_H:12.033:2003yCat.2246....0C ERR_H:0.039:2003yCat.2246....0C MAG_K:11.145:2003yCat.2246....0C ERR_K:0.033:2003yCat.2246....0C A_SKY:0.093:Major axis in arcmin, 2008ApJ...689..194S B_SKY:0.093:Minor axis in arcmin, 2008ApJ...689..194S THETA_SKY:90:Angle axis in degree, 2008ApJ...689..194S The second HDU, named n6803_E, contains the spectrum at the PN center, wavelength in um and flux in erg/s/cm2/A. The third HDU, named n6803_S, contains the spectrum at the PN halo, wavelength in um and flux in erg/s/cm2/A. Both headers of extension n6803_E and n6803_S are a copy of the original data header, see the CDS entry of NGC 6803 for more information.
Parameter.Source: Input proposed by Marco Scodeggio, data from CDS.

Parameter.title: GroundSegment.MER.StarGalaxySeparation.StarProbabilityCube
Parameter.Description: This cube is describing the probability of an object to be a star in a 3 dimensional space. (X = galactic latitude, Y = VIS magnitude, Z = VIS Mu_Max - VIS magnitude). The min and max limits on each axis are given in the associated StarProbabilityCubeLimits, except for glat for which all bin values are given in StarProbabilityCubeGlatAxis. The probability of each object to be a star will be: - either interpolated from the cube when its (X,Y,Z) position is inside the cube's limits, - or set to zero otherwise.
Parameter.Source: Based on SC3 simulations (only one galactic latitude, no binary stars, monochromatic PSF, magnitudes still computed with sextractor). Input by Elie. Current best estimate. See https://euclid.roe.ac.uk/projects/sgw/wiki/StarProbabilityCube_v11_for_SC456
